<span id="vi.iv.xiv"></span>

<span id="vi.iv.xiv-p1"></span> <span class="c1"><span
id="vi.iv.xiv-p1.1"></span>Chapter XIV.—Apostrophe.</span>

<span id="vi.iv.xiv-p2"></span>Albeit Israel washed daily all his limbs
over, yet is he never clean.  His *hands*, at all events, are ever
unclean, eternally dyed with the blood of the prophets, and of the Lord
Himself; and on that account, as being hereditary culprits from their
privity to their fathers’ crimes, <span
id="fr_8845"></span>[8846](#fn_8845.md) they do not dare even to raise them
unto the Lord, <span id="fr_8846"></span>[8847](#fn_8846.md) for fear some
Isaiah should cry out, <span id="fr_8847"></span>[8848](#fn_8847.md) for
fear Christ should utterly shudder.  We, however, not only raise, but
even expand them; and, taking our model from the Lord’s passion <span
id="fr_8848"></span>[8849](#fn_8848.md) even in prayer we confess <span
id="fr_8849"></span>[8850](#fn_8849.md) to Christ.

